            {
              "id": "9d9c1240-eb9b-35fe-9ed3-d8eed633fa39",
              "name": "Insecure Cookie Settings",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unset Domain in Default Session Middleware Settings Vulnerability\" in JavaScript is a security flaw that occurs when the domain attribute in the session cookie is not set. This can lead to session cookies being sent to all subdomains, which can potentially expose sensitive session data to malicious subdomains.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always set the domain attribute in the session cookie. This ensures that the session cookie is only sent to the specified domain and not to all subdomains.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```javascript\nvar express = require('express');\nvar session = require('express-session');\nvar cookieParser = require('cookie-parser');\n\nvar app = express();\n\napp.use(cookieParser());\napp.use(session({\n  secret: 'keyboard cat',\n  resave: true,\n  saveUninitialized: true,\n  cookie: { \n    secure: false,\n    domain: 'yourdomain.com' // Set your domain here\n  }\n}));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- express\n- express-session\n- cookie-parser\n\nYou can install these dependencies using npm:\n\n```bash\nnpm install express express-session cookie-parser\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-539: Information Exposure Through Persistent Cookies](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/539.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-539",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/539.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-539"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "9ddac073-078f-3f4f-be28-cec815d2e54b",
              "name": "Unescaped EJS Output Allows XSS Attacks",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"EJS Output Unescaped XSS Vulnerability Detected\" is a Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability that occurs when user input is outputted directly into the HTML without proper sanitization or encoding. This allows an attacker to inject malicious scripts into the web page, which can lead to various attacks such as stealing sensitive information, session hijacking, defacement of the website, etc.\n\nIn the given code snippet, the EJS template engine is used to output the product name directly into the HTML. If the product name contains any malicious scripts, they will be executed when the page is loaded.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always sanitize and/or encode user input before outputting it into the HTML. This can be done using various methods such as HTML encoding, JavaScript encoding, CSS encoding, URL encoding, etc. depending on the context.\n\nIn the context of EJS, use `<%= %>` instead of `<%- %>` to output the data. The `<%= %>` syntax automatically HTML-encodes the output, which prevents XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```javascript\n<td><%= output.products[i].name %></td>\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Express.js\n- EJS\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
