            {
              "id": "af85e538-7a8c-38df-928d-6f0e290f5ae1",
              "name": "Sensitive Data Exposure In API Response",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSensitive Data Exposure in API Response is a vulnerability that occurs when an API unintentionally exposes sensitive information in its responses. This can happen when a developer includes sensitive data in the response object without realizing it, or when the API is not properly configured to filter out sensitive data. In the provided JavaScript code, the vulnerability lies in the fact that all user data is being returned in the API response without any filtering or sanitization. This could potentially expose sensitive user information like passwords, credit card numbers, or personal identification numbers.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always filter and sanitize the data that is returned in an API response. Never return more information than is necessary. If possible, avoid returning sensitive data altogether. If you must return sensitive data, make sure it is properly encrypted.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```javascript\ndb.User.findAll({\n    attributes: ['id', 'name', 'email'] // Only return non-sensitive data\n}).then(users => {\n    res.status(200).json({\n        success: true,\n        users: users\n    })\n})\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, the `findAll` method is configured to only return the `id`, `name`, and `email` attributes of the user objects. This ensures that no sensitive data is exposed in the API response.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Express.js: A web application framework for Node.js.\n- Sequelize: A promise-based Node.js ORM for Postgres, MySQL, MariaDB, SQLite and Microsoft SQL Server.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP API Security: Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-api-security/)\n- [CWE-200: Information Exposure](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-200"
                ]
              }
